Nickel has a face-centered cubic (FCC) structure with a molar mass of 58.69 g/mol, a density of 8.83 g/cm³, and Avogadro's number \(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23}\) atoms/mol. The formula for density \(\rho\) in terms of the lattice parameter \(a\) is: \[ \rho = \frac{n \cdot M}{V \cdot N_A} \] where \(n = 4\) (for FCC), \(M = 58.69\) g/mol, and \(V = a^3\). Rearranging to solve for \(a\): \[ a^3 = \frac{n \cdot M}{\rho \cdot N_A} \] Substituting the given values: \[ a^3 = \frac{4 \cdot 58.69}{8.83 \cdot 6.022 \times 10^{23}} \approx \frac{234.76}{53.174 \times 10^{23}} \approx 4.423 \times 10^{-23} \text{ cm}^3 \] Taking the cube root to find \(a\): \[ a \approx (4.423 \times 10^{-23})^{1/3} \approx 3.57 \times 10^{-8} \text{ cm} = 357 \text{ pm} \] In an FCC structure, the second-nearest neighbor distance is \(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \times a\). Calculating this distance: \[ \text{Second-nearest neighbor distance} = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 357 \text{ pm} \approx 0.866 \times 357 \text{ pm} \approx 309.16 \text{ pm} \] Rounding to two decimal places, the second-nearest neighbor distance is: \[ \boxed{3.09 \times 10^2} \text{ pm} \]
